<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-analytic-functions"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Analytic Functions</title>

  <p>
    A function <m>f</m> is said to be <term>analytic at</term><idx>analytic
    at a point</idx> <m>x_0</m> if there exists a power series
    <me>
      \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n(x-x_0)^n
    </me>
    that converges to <m>f(x)</m> on some open interval containing
    <m>x_0</m>. We say that <m>f</m> is <term>analytic on</term><idx>analytic
    on an open set</idx> an open set <m>U \subseteq \R</m> if it is analytic
    at every point of <m>U</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Thus analytic functions are exactly those functions that locally agree
    with power series. The next result shows that such a representation, if it
    exists, is forced to be the Taylor series.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-analytic-functions-unique-taylor-series">
    <title>Analytic Functions Are Given by Their Taylor Series</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>f</m> is analytic at <m>x_0</m>. Then <m>f</m> is
        infinitely differentiable on some neighborhood of <m>x_0</m>, and
        there exists <m>r&gt;0</m> such that
        <me>
          f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{f^{(n)}(x_0)}{n!}(x-x_0)^n
          \qquad \text{for } |x-x_0|&lt;r.
        </me>
        In particular, the power series representation of <m>f</m> about
        <m>x_0</m> is unique.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>f</m> is analytic at <m>x_0</m>, there is a power series
        <me>
          f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n(x-x_0)^n
        </me>
        on some interval <m>|x-x_0|&lt;r</m>. By
        <xref ref="thm-termwise-calculus-power-series"/>, we may differentiate
        term by term on this interval. Repeating this process <m>k</m> times
        gives
        <me>
          f^{(k)}(x)
          =
          \sum_{n=k}^\infty n(n-1)\cdots(n-k+1)a_n(x-x_0)^{n-k}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Setting <m>x=x_0</m> leaves only the term with <m>n=k</m>, so
        <me>
          f^{(k)}(x_0)=k!a_k.
        </me>
        Hence
        <me>
          a_k=\frac{f^{(k)}(x_0)}{k!},
        </me>
        and substituting this into the original series gives the desired
        Taylor expansion. Since each coefficient is uniquely determined by
        <m>f</m>, the representation is unique.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    The theorem shows that analytic functions are automatically
    <m>C^\infty</m>. The converse is false: a function may be infinitely
    differentiable and still fail to agree with its Taylor series.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="eg-smooth-not-analytic">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define
        <me>
          f(x)=\begin{cases}
          e^{-1/x} &amp; \text{if } x&gt;0,\\
          0 &amp; \text{if } x\le 0.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Then <m>f</m> is infinitely differentiable on <m>\R</m>, and every
        derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>0</m> is equal to <m>0</m>. Therefore
        the Taylor series of <m>f</m> at <m>0</m> is the zero series.
        However, <m>f(x)&gt;0</m> for every <m>x&gt;0</m>, so <m>f</m> does
        not agree with that Taylor series on any neighborhood of <m>0</m>.
        Thus <m>f</m> is not analytic at <m>0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    The previous example shows that a smooth function may fail to agree with
    its Taylor series even when that Taylor series converges everywhere.
    There are also smooth functions whose Taylor series at a point does not
    converge anywhere except at that point.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="eg-smooth-divergent-taylor-series">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider
        <me>
          f(x)=\int_0^\infty e^{-t}\cos(t^2x)\,dt.
        </me>
        One can show, by differentiating under the integral sign, that
        <m>f</m> is <m>C^\infty</m> and that
        <me>
          f^{(n)}(0)=\begin{cases}
          0 &amp; \text{if } n \text{ is odd},\\
          \pm (2n)! &amp; \text{if } n \text{ is even}.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Consequently the Taylor coefficient
        <m>f^{(n)}(0)/n!</m> has absolute value <m>(2n)!/n!</m> for infinitely
        many <m>n</m>. Since
        <me>
          \frac{(2n)!}{n!}=(n+1)(n+2)\cdots(2n)\ge (n+1)^n,
        </me>
        the <m>n</m>-th roots of these coefficients tend to <m>\infty</m>.
        The root test therefore shows that the Taylor series of <m>f</m> at
        <m>0</m> has radius of convergence <m>0</m>. So this Taylor series
        diverges for every <m>x \ne 0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-borel-peano">
    <title>Borel-Peano Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For every formal power series
        <me>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n
        </me>
        there exists a function <m>f \in C^\infty(\R)</m> whose Taylor series
        at <m>0</m> is exactly
        <me>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    In other words, every formal power series occurs as the Taylor series of
    some smooth function, whether or not that series converges. For a readable
    account, see <xref ref="biblio-eom-borel-theorem"/> and the historical
    note <xref ref="biblio-besenyei-borel"/>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Further examples and discussion of non-analytic smooth functions can be
    found in <xref ref="biblio-boas-primer"/>.
  </p>
</section>
